BEGIN_TEXT
Calculate the following antiderivatives:
$PAR
(a) \( \displaystyle\int \frac{$a}{\cos^2 x} \,dx\) = \{ans_rule\} \( + C\).
$PAR
(b) \( \displaystyle\int \sec x(\sec x + \tan x) \,dx \) 
           = \{ans_rule\} \( + C\).
$PAR
(c) \( \displaystyle\int \frac{\sin(2x)}{\cos x} \, dx\) = \{ans_rule\} \( + C\). 
$PAR
${BBOLD}Hint:$EBOLD For some of these problems, you will need to change 
the form of the function being integrated before you take the
antiderivative. Appendix E in Anton has a good review of trigonometry.
END_TEXT

$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

##########################
$cc = -$c;
ANS(fun_cmp("${a}tan(x)", mode=>"antider"));
ANS(fun_cmp("tan(x) + 1/cos(x)", mode=>"antider"));
ANS(fun_cmp("-2cos(x)", mode=>"antider", vars=>"x", limits=>[.5,2]));
